My experiences at all chipotles have been wonderful including ones out of the state. This location is one that I have had the most trouble with. I came here once and there were fruit flies all over the place I tried to eat my food peacefully despite that up until I almost one of the fruit flies and i then asked for my bowl to be re-done and asked for it to go. I left that situation be and decided to go back in today and I had just gotten off my OWN restaurant job. I know how customers can be so I have a lot of respect for those in food service. There was only a little bit of chicken left in the container so I said can I get a little bit more of the chicken and a guy behind me who was sweeping (im assuming the manager or shift lead) said don’t worry about it ma’am they’re bringing a new batch of chicken I’ll make sure they put a bit more on there for you I said thank you and this girl comes from the back asking what condiments I would like and i said oh I’m waiting for the chicken because i wanted a bit more on there and she was basically saying I couldn’t have any. I explained to her I basically got chicken crumbs and she said no. I could’ve payed for extra if that is what she was saying but she immediately was speaking to me with attitude and I’m sure all of the employees noticed because they were just starring at her. I would like for something to be done about this.

Ordering at this Chipotle should be an Olympic sport considering how fast you need to decide on what you want. This is going to sound like a good thing but it’s not. The ordering process is too fast. I don’t even have time to think about what I want that I’m being asked if I want black or pinto beans on the burrito that I have yet to order. The employees speak before the customers do, and you better be sure of what you want because if you wanted green salsa instead, too bad so sad you meal is in the bag. Great job on efficiency guys, but let’s breathe a little. Also, the music sometimes is far too loud and the playlist choice is questionable. Food is good though so nothing to say on that.

I don't understand how anyone can think this is good food. Service was fine but the way they make the burrito makes no sense. First off the whole thing is cold- you have to make a burrito and then let it sit on the grill when it's done so it heats up. There is no grill here so the burrito will be cold. The meat is dry and has almost no flavor. Rice- really? You put rice on a burrito? Next you find out this monstrosity costs almost 11 dollars. Completely insane. This is Chicago- you can close your eyes and stumble into a restaurant serving amazing Mexican food anywhere and somehow this passes as real food?
